the educational gradient in health evidence from china events at stanford the educational gradient in health evidence from china facebook twitter email print add to calendar ceas colloquium qiulin chen ceas visiting scholar stanford university karen eggleston asia health policy program director shorenstein aparc stanford university in addition to the health protective effects of higher income and social status better education appears to be an important contributor to good health however evidence is limited from developing countries undergoing rapid socioeconomic transition like china to document the evolution of the educational gradient in health we analyze the china national health services survey ministry of health 1998 2003 and 2008 and the chinese family panel study peking university 2010 we find patterns consistent with the economic theory of socioeconomic gradients in health as modified to take account of china's rapid economic demographic and epidemiologic transitions over the past quarter century when thursday november 17 2011 4 15 pm approximate duration of 1.5 hour s where philippines conference room encina hall 3rd floor map audience faculty staff alumni friends general public students tags lecture reading humanities international sponsor center for east asian studies and asia health policy program shorenstein aparc contact 723 3363 hlee17 stanford edu admission free and open to the public permalink http events stanford edu events 289 28911 last modified september 15 2011
